Use conditional compilation or the `MAUI` platform-specific folders pattern. The cleanest approach:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives in the corresponding `Platforms/` folder (e.g., `Platforms/Android/AndroidNotificationService.cs`), which is already conditionally compiled per-platform by the SDK.

**Alternative** — avoid `#if` directives by placing a partial class or registration helper inside each platform folder:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/PlatformServices.cs
public static partial class PlatformServices
{
    public static partial void Register(IServiceCollection services)
        => services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, AndroidNotificationService>();
}
```

Then in `MauiProgram.cs`:
```csharp
PlatformServices.Register(builder.Services);
```

Both approaches are safe — the platform folders are only compiled for their target, so no missing-type errors on other platforms.
